metadata.name: Riding High N' Sitting Low
metadata.description:
Riding high and sitting low are terms used to describe the position of a vehicle's suspension.

Riding high refers to a vehicle that has a high ground clearance, which means there is a significant distance between the bottom of the vehicle and the ground. This can be due to a number of factors, including the type of vehicle (such as a truck or SUV), the size of the tires, or the suspension setup. A vehicle that is riding high may have a higher center of gravity and may be more prone to tipping or rolling over in sharp turns.

Sitting low, on the other hand, refers to a vehicle that has a low ground clearance. This means that the bottom of the vehicle is close to the ground and there is less distance between the vehicle and the ground. Low-riding vehicles may have a lower center of gravity, which can make them more stable and easier to handle at high speeds.
